Qd5 $1 {Usually, in the Spanish, White would like to attack on the kingside;
in order to do that, he concentrates pieces there. Black has a lot of good
moves; however, the best way is to create the counterattack. He can achieve
that with the very active Qd5; the idea is to eyeball the g2-square. The
threat is to jump with the knight to d4.} (20... Kh8 $5) (20... h6 $5) (20...
Rab8 $5) 21. Bb1 Kh8 {Another very precise move. You need to calculate
correctly what is happening on the board and pay attention to your opponent's
threats. White not only defends against Nd4, but also prepares Ba2, pinning
the queen to the king.} 22. Ba2 Qxc5 {Till now, Black is a pawn up with a
better position. Calculation doesn't mean to foresee 10 moves ahead, but to
understand what is going on and don't miss the simple tactics.} 23. d4 Qd6 (
23... exd4 {This was preferable.}) 24. dxe5 Nxe5 25. Rad1 Qc5 {This situation
